            <entry xml:id="entry_Atynæg" xml:lang="os-x-iron">
                <form xml:id="form_d4071e66" type="lemma"><orth>Atynæg</orth></form>
                <usg><lang/></usg>
                <sense xml:id="sense_d4071e72"><def xml:lang="ru">летний праздник перед началом сенокоса; связан,
                        по-видимому, со старым растительным культом; более известен у осетин,
                        живущих по Военно-Грузинской дороге (сел. Коби), и у соседящих с ними
                        грузинских племен, хевсур, пшавов, мохевцев, под названием
                        (<bibl/>)</def><def xml:lang="en">summer holiday before haymaking;
                        associated, apparently, with an old plant cult; better known among the
                        Ossetians living along the Georgian Military Road (village Kobi), and among
                        the neighboring Georgian tribes, Khevsurs, Pshavs, Mokhevtsy, by the name of
                            <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d4071e79" xml:lang="ka"><lang/>
                            <w/></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d4071e84" xml:lang="ka"><w>Atangenoba</w></mentioned> (<bibl><biblScope xml:lang="ru">ს. მაკალათია, 1934, p. 249</biblScope><biblScope xml:lang="en">ს.
                                მაკალათია, 1934, p. 249</biblScope></bibl>)</def></sense>
                <abv:exampleGrp xml:id="exampleGrp_d4071e94">
                    <abv:example xml:id="example_d4071e96">
                        <quote>Atynæg</quote>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>Erntefest am 3 Sonntag im Juli</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#src_Munk."/><biblScope>220</biblScope></bibl>
                    </abv:example>
                    <abv:example xml:id="example_d4071e110" xml:lang="ru">
                        <quote><q rendition="#rend_doublequotes">Атинаг</q> — праздник сенокоса</quote>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q><q rendition="#rend_doublequotes">Atinag</q> — a haymaking feast</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <bibl><biblScope xml:lang="ru">Закавказский вестник № 32,
                                1855</biblScope><biblScope xml:lang="en">Zakavkazskiy vestnik № 32,
                                1855</biblScope></bibl>
                    </abv:example>
                    <abv:example xml:id="example_d4071e121">
                        <quote>rast Atynægæj Kæxcgænæny astæw mīt waryn bajdydta</quote>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>как раз между (праздниками) <hi rendition="#rend_smallcaps">Atynæg%s и %sKæxcgænæn</hi> пошел снег</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>just between (the holidays) <hi rendition="#rend_smallcaps">Atynæg%s and %sKæxcgænæn</hi> it
                                snowed</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#src_Сека"/><biblScope>44</biblScope></bibl>
                    </abv:example>
                </abv:exampleGrp>
                <etym xml:lang="ru">Названия осетинских праздников и божеств в большинстве восходят
                    к названиям христианских „святых“: <ref type="xr" target="#entry_Wastyrǵi"/>,
                        <ref type="xr" target="#entry_Wacilla"/>, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_Tūtyr"/>, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_Nikkola"/>, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_Mykalgabyrtæ"/>. В этом направлении следует искать
                    также разъяснения <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d4071e221" xml:id="mentioned_d4071e154" xml:lang="os"><lang/>
                        <w>Atynæg</w></mentioned>, <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d4071e226" xml:id="mentioned_d4071e159" xml:lang="ka"><lang/>
                        <w>Atengenoba</w></mentioned>, ср. св. <hi rendition="#rend_italic">Афиноген</hi>, <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d4071e231" xml:id="mentioned_d4071e164" xml:lang="grc"><lang/>
                        <w>’Αθηνογενης</w></mentioned>. Культ Афиногена Севастийского был популярен
                    в древнехристианской церкви (см.: <bibl><biblScope xml:lang="ru">Кекелидзе.
                            Иерусалимский канонарь VII в. 1912, стр. 18—20</biblScope></bibl>). На
                    кавказской почве можно еще указать на <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d4071e240" xml:id="mentioned_d4071e173" xml:lang="ka"><lang/>
                        <w>Atenagani</w>
                        <gloss><q>Sunday of Thomas</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Чубинов"/></bibl>), <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d4071e252" xml:id="mentioned_d4071e185" xml:lang="inh"><lang/>
                        <w>Eting</w></mentioned> и, может быть, на <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d4071e257" xml:id="mentioned_d4071e190" xml:lang="ab"><lang/>
                        <w>Aθunəha</w>
                        <gloss><q>молитва по поводу засухи</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><biblScope xml:lang="ru">Xp. Вост. V, вып. III, 1917, стр.
                            163</biblScope></bibl>).%n<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>93</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
                <etym xml:lang="en">The names of Ossetian holidays and deities usually go back to
                    the names of Christian saints: cf. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_Wastyrǵi"/>,
                        <ref type="xr" target="#entry_Wacilla"/>, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_Tūtyr"/>, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_Nikkola"/>, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_Mykalgabyrtæ"/>. In this direction, one should also
                    seek explanations for <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d4071e154" xml:id="mentioned_d4071e221" xml:lang="os"><lang/>
                        <w>Atynæg</w></mentioned>, <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d4071e159" xml:id="mentioned_d4071e226" xml:lang="ka"><lang/>
                        <w>Atengenoba</w></mentioned>, cf. Saint <hi rendition="#rend_italic">Athenogen</hi>, <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d4071e164" xml:id="mentioned_d4071e231" xml:lang="grc"><lang/>
                        <w>’Αθηνογενης</w></mentioned>. The cult of Athenogen of Sevastia was
                    popular in the ancient Christian church (see: <bibl><biblScope xml:lang="en">Kekelidze. Jerusalem cannon, VII century. 1912, pp.
                        18-20</biblScope></bibl>). On the Caucasian ground, one can also point at
                        <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d4071e173" xml:id="mentioned_d4071e240" xml:lang="ka"><lang/>
                        <w>Atenagani</w>
                        <gloss><q>Sunday of Thomas</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Чубинов"/></bibl>), <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d4071e185" xml:id="mentioned_d4071e252" xml:lang="inh"><lang/>
                        <w>Eting</w></mentioned> and, perhaps, at <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d4071e190" xml:id="mentioned_d4071e257" xml:lang="ab"><lang/>
                        <w>Aθunəha</w>
                        <gloss><q>prayer for drought</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><biblScope xml:lang="en">Chr. Vost. V, Vol. III, 1917, p.
                            163</biblScope></bibl>).%n<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>93</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
